Step 1: Identify the cash component. From the balance sheet we see the following cash accounts at period end: 
• Cash on Hand = 3,730,866.78  
• Bank Deposits = 3,938,781.80  
These two items total the cash and cash equivalents:  
  Cash and Cash Equivalents = 3,730,866.78 + 3,938,781.80 = 7,669,648.58

Step 2: Identify Current Liabilities. The balance sheet shows:  
  Total Current Liabilities = 829,755.77

Step 3: Calculate the Cash to Current Debt Ratio by dividing the total cash by total current liabilities.  
  Ratio = Cash and Cash Equivalents / Total Current Liabilities  
    = 7,669,648.58 / 829,755.77  
    ≈ 9.25

Thus, the Cash to Current Debt Ratio is approximately 9.25.
